\begin_layout Section
Asymptotic result, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 known
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that our sample mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

, should be close to the population mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 So when giving a region of values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 that are consistent with the observed data, we would expect our CI formula
 to be something like 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{x}-d,\;\bar{x}+d\right)$
\end_inset

 for some value 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 That value of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 should be small if our sample size is big, representing our faith that
 a large amount of data should result in a statistic that is 
\emph on
very
\emph default
 close to the true value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that if our data 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\sim N\left(\mu,\,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 or our sample size was large enough, then we know
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{X}\sim N\left(\mu,\,\;\sigma_{\bar{X}}^{2}=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}\right)
\]

\end_inset

or is approximately so.
 Doing a little re-arranging, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\left(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)}\sim N\left(0,1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So if we take the 0.025 and 0.975 quantiles of the normal distribution, which
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0.025}=-1.96$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0.975}=1.96$
\end_inset

, we could write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
0.95 & = & P\left(-1.96\le\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\le1.96\right)\\
 & =\\
 &  & P\left(-1.96\left(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)\le\bar{X}-\mu\le1.96\left(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)\right)\\
\\
 & = & P\left(\bar{X}-1.96\left(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)\le\mu\le\bar{X}+1.96\left(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Which suggests that a reasonable 95% Confidence Interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}\pm1.96\left(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In general for a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-\alpha\right)\cdot100\%$
\end_inset

 confidence interval, we would use the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}\pm z_{1-\alpha/2}\left(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that I could write the formula using 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{\alpha/2}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1-\alpha/2}$
\end_inset

 because the normal distribution is symmetric about 0 and we are subtracting
 and adding the same quantity to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interpretation of a confidence interval is that over repeated sampling,
 
\begin_inset Formula $100(1-\alpha)\%$
\end_inset

 of the resulting intervals will contain the population mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 but we don't know if the interval we have actually observed is one of the
 good intervals that contains the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 or not.
 Since this is quite the mouthful, we will say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

we are 
\begin_inset Formula $100\left(1-\alpha\right)\%$
\end_inset

 confident that the observed interval contains the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example: Suppose a bottling facility has a machine that supposedly fills
 bottles to 300 milliliters (ml) and is known to have a standard deviation
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=3$
\end_inset

 ml.
 However, the machine occasionally gets out of calibration and might be
 consistently overfilling or under-filling bottles.
 To discover if the machine is calibrated correctly, we take a random sample
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=40$
\end_inset

 bottles and observe the mean amount filled was 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}=299$
\end_inset

 ml.
 We calculate a 
\begin_inset Formula $95\%$
\end_inset

 confidence interval (CI) to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\bar{x} & \pm & z_{1-\alpha/2}\left(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)\\
299 & \pm & 1.96\left(\frac{3}{\sqrt{40}}\right)\\
299 & \pm & 0.93
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and conclude that we are 
\begin_inset Formula $95\%$
\end_inset

 confident that the that the true mean fill amount is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[298.07,299.93\right]$
\end_inset

 and that the machine has likely drifted off calibration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Confidence interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is unknown
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is unrealistic to expect that we know the population variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 but do not know the population mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 So in calculations that involve 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, we want to use the sample standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 instead.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our previous results about confidence intervals assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\sim N\left(\mu,\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 (or is approximately so) and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sqrt{\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}}}\sim N\left(0,1\right).
\]

\end_inset

I want to just replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 but the sample variance 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 is also a random variable and incorporating it into the standardization
 function might affect the distribution.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sqrt{\frac{S^{2}}{n}}}\sim\;???
\]

\end_inset

Unfortunately this substitution of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 comes with a cost and this quantity is not normally distributed.
 Instead it has a t-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 However as the sample size increases and 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 becomes a more reliable estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, this penalty should become smaller.
\end_layout

