\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the sample standard deviation into the confidence interval
 formula, we also substitute a t-quantile for the standard normal quantile.
 We will denote 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n-1}^{1-\alpha/2}$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\alpha/2$
\end_inset

 quantile of a t-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 Therefore we will use the following formula for the calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $100\left(1-\alpha\right)\%$
\end_inset

 confidence intervals for the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{x}\pm t_{n-1}^{1-\alpha/2}\left(\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notation: We will be calculating confidence intervals for the rest of the
 course and it is useful to recognize the skeleton of a confidence interval
 formula.
 The basic form is always the same
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Estimate\;\pm\,t_{df}^{1-\alpha/2}\,\,Standard\,Error\left(\,Estimate\,\right)
\]

\end_inset

In our current problem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 is our estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and the estimated standard deviation (which is commonly called the 
\emph on
standard error
\emph default
) is 
\begin_inset Formula $s/\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

 and the appropriate degrees of freedom are 
\begin_inset Formula $df=n-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

