\begin_layout Section
Sample Size Selection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often a researcher is in the position of asking how many sample observations
 are necessary to achieve a specific width of confidence interval.
 Let the 
\emph on
margin of error, 
\emph default
which we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $ME$
\end_inset

, be the half-width desired (so the confidence interval would be 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}\pm ME$
\end_inset

).
 So given the desired confidence level, and if we know 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, then we can calculate the necessary number of samples to achieve a particular
 
\begin_inset Formula $ME$
\end_inset

.
 To do this calculation, we must also have some estimate of the population
 standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ME=z_{1-\alpha/2}\left(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\approx\left[z_{1-\alpha/2}\left(\frac{\sigma}{ME}\right)\right]^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that because 
\begin_inset Formula $n\propto\left[\frac{1}{ME}\right]^{2}$
\end_inset

 then if we want a margin of error that is twice as precise (i.e.
 the CI is half as wide) then we need to quadruple our sample size! Second,
 this result requires having some knowledge of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 We could acquire an estimate through: 1) a literature search, 2) a pilot
 study, or 3) expert opinion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
A researcher is interested in estimating the mean weight of an adult elk
 in Yellowstone's northern herd after the winter and wants to obtain a 
\begin_inset Formula $90\%$
\end_inset

 confidence interval with a half-width 
\begin_inset Formula $ME=10$
\end_inset

 pounds.
 Using prior collection data from the fall harvest (road side checks by
 game wardens), the researcher believes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=60$
\end_inset

 lbs is a reasonable standard deviation number to use.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
n & \approx & \left[z_{0.95}\left(\frac{\sigma}{ME}\right)\right]^{2}\\
 & = & \left[1.645\left(\frac{60}{10}\right)\right]^{2}\\
 & = & 97.41
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that I don't bother using the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-distribution in this calculations because because I am assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is known.
 While this is a horrible assumption, the difference between using a 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 quantile instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 quantile is small and what really matters is how good the estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is.
 As with many things, the quality of the input values is reflected in the
 quality of the output.
 Typically this sort of calculation is done with only a rough estimate of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and therefore I would subsequently regard the resulting sample size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 as an equally rough estimate.
\end_layout

